how that inspired you.

00:00:30.162 --> 00:00:32.065 line:0%
So, it really did,
because I was reading, um,

00:00:32.098 --> 00:00:34.200 line:0%
<i> Where the Red Fern Grows </i>
by Wilson Rawls,

00:00:34.233 --> 00:00:36.669 line:0%
I was reading the<i> Shiloh</i> series,
and I read<i> Old Yeller,</i>

00:00:36.702 --> 00:00:38.604 line:0%
-and, basically,<i> Where the... </i>
-Right.<i> Old Yeller,</i>

00:00:38.637 --> 00:00:41.841 line:0%
-really, really sad. Yeah, yeah.
-Yeah, it is.

00:00:41.874 --> 00:00:44.110
But I read, um,<i> Where the Red
 Fern Grows,</i> and that's about

00:00:44.143 --> 00:00:46.646
a boy who saves his money
to buy a dog to help him hunt.

00:00:46.679 --> 00:00:49.582
And then the<i> Shiloh</i> series
is about a boy who finds a dog

00:00:49.615 --> 00:00:51.818
-and uses him on a farm. And<i> Old
 Yeller</i> is about a boy -Right.

00:00:51.851 --> 00:00:53.986
-who finds a dog and
then uses him on a farm. -Yeah.

00:00:54.019 --> 00:00:56.322
So they were all really
the same.

00:00:56.355 --> 00:00:58.491
-But I noticed that when I went
home and read the books -Yeah.

00:00:58.524 --> 00:01:00.426
that I wanted to, like,
about black girls,

00:01:00.459 --> 00:01:02.562
they were all different. Like,
sometimes I was reading about

00:01:02.595 --> 00:01:04.430
student council. Sometimes
I was reading about a girl

00:01:04.463 --> 00:01:06.833
who went to Africa.
So it was always different.

00:01:06.866 --> 00:01:08.901
-It was never, like, the same
plot I was hearing over -Yeah.

00:01:08.934 --> 00:01:10.903
-and over. -And these books
weren't in your schools.

00:01:10.936 --> 00:01:13.306
-They weren't in my school, no.
-Right. Man, interesting.

00:01:13.339 --> 00:01:15.441
-And-and your name is Marley.
That's such a cool name. -Yes.

00:01:15.474 --> 00:01:17.376
-Were you named after Bob
Marley? Really? -Yes, my mother

00:01:17.409 --> 00:01:20.313
is Jamaican, so she named me
after Bob Marley.

00:01:20.346 --> 00:01:22.982
Wow, that is amazing,
'cause it's-it's ironic...

00:01:23.015 --> 00:01:25.518
-(cheering and applause)
-Well, they're clapping.

00:01:25.551 --> 00:01:28.121
What's ironic to me is
that there's actually a movie

00:01:28.154 --> 00:01:30.523
called<i> Marley and Me </i>
about a white boy and his dog.

00:01:30.556 --> 00:01:33.126
-Yes, I know.
-It's kind of ironic, you know?

00:01:33.159 --> 00:01:35.128
Have you ever thought
of collecting 1,000 movies

00:01:35.161 --> 00:01:36.996
and giving them out to schools?

00:01:37.029 --> 00:01:39.065
Yes. That would be an idea.

00:01:39.098 --> 00:01:40.933
So let me ask you a question.
So why do you think

00:01:40.966 --> 00:01:43.603
it is important to read a book
with someone who's like you?

00:01:43.636 --> 00:01:46.405
Like, what was it that really
made that important to you?

00:01:46.438 --> 00:01:49.942
Well, it really was because when
you read a story about a person

00:01:49.975 --> 00:01:52.478
that you can connect with...
So, like, you host a TV show.

00:01:52.511 --> 00:01:55.214
-Yeah. -So, if you were to read
a book about a black man

00:01:55.247 --> 00:01:57.350
who hosts a TV show,
then you would remember

00:01:57.383 --> 00:02:01.420
-whatever he learned so you
could use it on the show. -What?

00:02:01.453 --> 00:02:04.957
-Could you go collect some
of those books, maybe? -Yes.

00:02:04.990 --> 00:02:07.493
Could the, uh... could the black
late-night host have a dog?

00:02:07.526 --> 00:02:09.829
Maybe, yeah. If you want.

00:02:09.862 --> 00:02:13.032
Um, how-how surprised were you
that there were so many books?

00:02:13.065 --> 00:02:14.767
'Cause you collected... How
many books have you collected?

00:02:14.800 --> 00:02:17.170
-Uh, about 1,000. -Were
you surprised how many books

00:02:17.203 --> 00:02:19.372
-there were out there?
-Yes. I knew that there was

00:02:19.405 --> 00:02:21.240
a lot of children's books,
because when you're a kid,

00:02:21.273 --> 00:02:23.242
they push reading so much,
for you to learn all that stuff.

00:02:23.275 --> 00:02:25.511
But when you get older, like,
books become, like, scarce,

00:02:25.544 --> 00:02:27.213
and you only read
normally one type.

00:02:27.246 --> 00:02:30.082
So I was like, "Whoa, I didn't
know that I was missing out

00:02:30.115 --> 00:02:33.019
on so many books in my school."
But... Because when I get older,

00:02:33.052 --> 00:02:35.421
I just kind of have to read
book club books about white boys

00:02:35.454 --> 00:02:37.924
and their dogs, and it just
kind of... it becomes, like,

00:02:37.957 --> 00:02:40.459
-all of my day. So... -I bet
there's a book club out there.

00:02:40.492 --> 00:02:42.795
"All right, this is the White
Boy, Dog Book Club, everybody.

00:02:42.828 --> 00:02:46.399
Uh, today's book,
<i> White Boy and His Dog."</i>

00:02:46.432 --> 00:02:47.934
Have you...
What has been the action...

00:02:47.967 --> 00:02:49.602
the reaction with
your classmates and everything?

00:02:49.635 --> 00:02:51.604
-Well, they've been really proud
of me. -Oh, cool.

00:02:51.637 --> 00:02:53.539
So they've been, like,
high-fiving me and saying,

00:02:53.572 --> 00:02:56.209
"Congrats on your 1,000.
I hope you get 1,000 more."

00:02:56.242 --> 00:02:57.877
So they've been
really supportive for me.

00:02:57.910 --> 00:03:00.112
Have any white boys with dogs
congratulated you?

00:03:00.145 --> 00:03:02.515
-Yes, actually, they have.
-Really?

00:03:02.548 --> 00:03:05.184
Because sometimes they're sick
of reading those stories, too.

00:03:05.217 --> 00:03:06.519
That's hilarious.

00:03:06.552 --> 00:03:07.720
They're like, "Finally!

00:03:07.753 --> 00:03:09.922
-Finally, a different story!"
-Yeah.

00:03:09.955 --> 00:03:13.392
That's great. Um...

00:03:13.425 --> 00:03:15.595
Uh, now, it's interesting,
'cause, uh,

00:03:15.628 --> 00:03:17.897
I love the selflessness
of what you're doing.

00:03:17.930 --> 00:03:19.832
